AGI - After almost four hours, the summit on Ukraine ended at Eliseo > convened by French President Emmanuel Macron>. The purpose of the meeting was to tighten the lines in front of the activism of American President Donald Trump, who agreed with Russian President Vladimir Putin to start a negotiation from which for now seem excluded not only Europeans, but also Ukraine.
&nbsp;
Among the themes in question, the possible sending of European troops as deterrent. But several countries have already braked. Like the German Chancellor Olof Scholz, the first to leave the Elysée, who clarified that a discussion about this is "inappropriate and premature".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
At the Elysée there were also the secretary general of NATO, Mark Rutte >e the Ue>, Antonio Costa and Ursula von der Leyen. Prior to the beginning of the meeting, Macron had a telephone interview with American President Donald Trump.&nbsp; The Polish Prime Minister, Donald Tusk>, said that all participants at the Paris European Summit on Ukraine have manifested "the like". Tusk, at a press point held after the talks, reports the Guardian, explained that during the meeting no binding decisions were made but that it was important to align the views of all the allies.
&nbsp;
Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelensky used hard tones to describe the line chosen by Donald Trump to end the war in Ukraine. American president wants to "compose" Vladimir Putin, said on German television Ard. "The problem is that the United States today say things that are very welcome to Putin. I think that's where the problem is. Because they want to please him," he said in the interview recorded last Saturday.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
On the other hand, the leaders of Russian diplomacy, Serghei Lavrov, and the United States, Marco Rubio, will open negotiations in Saudi capital on Tuesday to normalize bilateral relations and lay the foundations for a possible solution to the war in Ukraine. Outside Europe, while Kiev reiterates that it will not accept any agreement that does not see it involved. "I don't know what role Europeans could play at the negotiating table," Lavrov said in a press conference before leaving for the Saudi capital. "If they just want to extort ideas to freeze the conflict, why invite them?", the Russian minister took the dose.
&nbsp;
The United States, at the Munich Conference on Security, warned that European countries would not take part in the negotiations. Moscow has long maintained this position, citing as an argument the lack of respect for the Minsk agreements by Kiev, Berlin and Paris ten years ago. Riad talks will take place against the background of a possible meeting between the leadership of the Kremlin, Vladimir Putin, and the White House, Donald Trump, who last week, in a telephone conversation, agreed to negotiate the end of the war in Ukraine.
&nbsp;
Although it was already known that Rubio would go to Riad, he was the Kremlin to announce the meeting, to which Yuri Ushakov, diplomat advisor of Putin will participate. "It is expected that tomorrow they will hold a meeting with their American counterparts in Riad, which will focus mainly on restoring the entire range of Russian-American relations," said the Kremlin spokesman, Dmitri Peskov.
&nbsp;
It will be the first meeting between a Russian Foreign Minister and an American Secretary of State > after that held in January 2022, > a month before the beginning of the war: at the time the bilateral was between Lavrov and his counterpart Antony Blinken, under the democratic administration of Joe Biden.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>Scholz: "Next with support in Kiev, no a diktat"</h2>
No to a "peace imposed by diktat to Ukraine", says the German Chancellor, Olaf Scholz, leaving the Elysée after the summit. "Ukraine cannot accept everything that is presented to her, under no circumstances," he added. "Ukraine can trust us," Europeans "will continue to support" Kiev.
<h2>Washington, do not consider meetings of Riad a negotiation</h2>
The meetings scheduled tomorrow at Riyadh among Russian and American officials should not be considered as a "negotiated" on Ukraine, said Tammy Bruce, spokesman of the State Department, according to which the American President, Donald Trump, charged the delegates to "be followed effectively" his last Wednesday call with the Russian President, Vladimir Putin. "I don't think people should see this as something about details or progress in the context of some negotiation," he added.
<h2>Wp, Europeans survey the U.S., ready to send a force of 30 thousand soldiers
European leaders are deciding on sending troops to Ukraine as part of a ceasefire agreement and are also proving Trump's team on what kind of US military support they would get, writes the Washington Post citing four sources familiar with the dossier. According to the Post, the European plan would provide a force of "deterrence" of a few brigades, perhaps 250,000 to 300,000 soldiers, who would not be stationed along the contact line but would be ready to intervene as a demonstration of strength if the Russian forces tried to reboot the war.
&nbsp;
European demands on the U.S. would include intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance, as well as potential aerial coverage or some kind of aid in the air defenses to protect the force, said sources agreeing that US support would be fundamental and that would welcome clear warnings from Washington to Russia, in public or private form, against any attempt to attack the force or rekindle a conflict in full rule. Another key issue for Europeans is how to respond if Russia should attack the European force: on the table the possibility to enter a mutual defence clause among the countries involved in the European coalition, which would not operate under the NATO flag.&nbsp; But for the German Chancellor Scholz "it is highly inappropriate to discuss it now". >
&nbsp;
<h2> Oppositions, Meloni come to the Chamber on the line of Italy</h2>
An urgent statement by the President of the Council Giorgia Meloni on the line of Italy on the developments of war in Ukraine. To ask it are the oppositions, intervening after the vote of trust on the decree Pnrr-Emergenze. Fratoianni di Avs: "Meloni will soon come to the House to report the government's position on what is happening in the world," starting from the "possible road map" on peace in Ukraine, and especially in the light of tomorrow's meeting in Riad between the US and Russia "in which Europe does not exist".
&nbsp;
Of the same notice the external manager of the Pd Peppe Provenzano: "I join Avs' request, we are witnessing the end of yesterday's world, the allies of the past today shoulder right extremists and exclude Europe from negotiation for Ukraine: is a direct attack on the integration process. Meloni must come to the court to tell us where he wants to be. If you want, today that the cornerstones of our place in the world are at stake, help to resurrect Europe or bury it under others' pickets." Finally, M5s, which, with Francesco Silvestri, is associated with the request but not with a simple statement but with communications from the premier, which envisages the vote on the resolutions at the end. "We need the House to express itself with a vote," he explained.
&nbsp;
