AGI - Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan awaits tomorrow in Turkish capital Ankara the Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky. A visit that arrives at a time that could be crucial in the developments of the conflict between Moscow and Kiev, to stop which Erdogan tried in vain in the recent past to mediate between Zelensky and Russian President Vladimir Putin.
&nbsp;
Zelensky's visit gives Erdogan the opportunity to press the Ukrainian leader to open a peace agreement, even if conditions were difficult to accept for Kiev. Yesterday the Turkish Foreign Minister, Hakan Fidan, said that "the territorial integrity of Ukraine is no longer realistic".
&nbsp;
Words that make it clear that reality in the field has convinced Ankara that peace "right", so desired by Erdogan, is no longer possible. The Turkish leader had prepared a draft peace plan on the occasion of the G20 in Rio de Janeiro last November, except to decide to wait for the settlement of Donald Trump. The entry into the scene of the new American president Donald Trump could change the balances and lead to peace. This is the hope of Erdogan, who commented on the recent call between Putin and Trump stating that "wait positive developments".
&nbsp;
Trump's dialogue with Putin and the end of unconditional support in Kiev guaranteed by the administration led by Joe Biden could help convince Zelensky. The plan of the Turkish leader in fact plans to stop hostilities as the first step, postpone the discussion about the entry of Ukraine into NATO and create a demilitarized area in Donbass, region that since 2014 is at the center of clashes and is gradually ended under Russian control.
&nbsp;
In support of Ukrainian troops Ankara proposes the sending of an international contingent, which acts as a guarantor and support in return for the postponement of the dialogue for the entry of Kiev into NATO. A realistic plan also reported by the Bloomberg agency, whose sources define "based on the field situation" and intelligence reports that Ukraine could soon lose much more substantial portions of territory. To convince Zelensky Erdogan will play the paper of collaboration in the defense.
&nbsp;
Ankara not only provides war drones in Kiev for years, but could guarantee supplies and implement the agreement, already signed, which provides for the construction of components of war aircraft without pilot directly on Ukrainian soil.
&nbsp;
Erdogan in recent months has often reiterated Turkey's willingness to host a peace conference with the presidents of Russia and Ukraine; an idea so far gone blank, but that could come back current in light of current developments, especially if Trump really pushes for the end of the conflict between Moscow and Kiev.

