AGI - Xi Jinping reassures private entrepreneurship by ensuring that the development policies launched by the government will be pursued even if in the perimeter of the fundamental principles of the socialist system. "They cannot change and will not change," said the Chinese president during a meeting with the leaders of the country's leading technological companies. The meeting is the first of the genus hosted by Xi since 2018 and takes place in a period of strong crisis of the Chinese private sector caused by a volatile mix of economic problems, including the increasing geopolitical tensions with the United States. "The difficulties and challenges that private economy faces are temporary, not long-term. They can be exceeded," said Xi, according to the state broadcaster CCTV.
&nbsp;
It is the right time for private companies and entrepreneurs to show their talents and give significant contributions, added the president. The trust of entrepreneurs and investors in China has been diminished by a slow internal economic recovery, by the duties and repressive measures taken against some companies accused of having a monopolistic attitude. Although Beijing has issued new laws to promote and protect the private sector, these efforts have often been weakened by contradictory actions by local authorities. Some local authorities, deprived of the income that came from the real estate sector after the explosion of the speculative bubble that overwhelmed colossi as Evergrande began to cash with heavy fines to enterprises.
&nbsp;
Xi also promised to remove barriers to competition: "We will constantly paint ahead the opening of competitive infrastructure sectors to a variety of market entities and we will make great efforts to solve financing difficulties and high funding costs for private companies," he said. The efforts to address the problem of arrears in payments due to private companies, as well as the fight against fines and arbitrary inspections, will also be the main priorities of the future, added Xi speaking in front of Jack Ma>, founder of Alibaba Group; Lei Jun>, founder and CEO of Xiaomi; Pony Ma Huateng>, founder and CEO of Tencent; Wang Chuanfu>, president and CEO of BYD electric car manufacturer; and Ren Zhengfei>, founder and CEO of Huawei Technologies. There were also Premier Li Qiang>; Wang Huning>, head of the top Chinese political advisory body, and Deputy Prime Minister Ding Xuexiang>. Other corporate personalities present at the symposium included Zeng Yuqun>, president of the colossus of CATL batteries; Leng Youbin>, president and CEO of the supplier of powdered milk for Feihe children; Nan Cunhui>, Chairman of the Electric Device Company Zhejiang Chint Electrics; Wang Xingxing>, founder of the Unitree Robotics Company; Liu Yonghao>, president of animal feed producer New Hope; and Yu Renrong>, founder and president of Will Semiconductor.&nbsp;&nbsp;

