AGI -&nbsp;For 42% of European citizens between 16 and 30 years, social media is the main source of information on political and social issues, while television is the second most popular source (39%). The preference for TV is, on the other hand, more evident between 25 and 30 years, an age group even more likely to use online news platforms and radio > compared to 16-18 year olds, who rely more on social media (45%) than 25-30 years (39%) and trust friends, family or colleagues for information (29% compared to 23%). These are the results of the Eurobarometer flash on youth, the European Parliament poll published today.
&nbsp;
<h2> In Italy
With regard to Italy, in the citizens between 16 and 30 years is instead the TV the most widely used mass media > for political and social information (52%), followed by social media (44%) and press and online news platforms (25%). Among social media, Instagram is the most used, with 59% compared to the average of 47% in EU, followed by TikTok with 35% (39% EU) and YouTube at 37% (37% in EU). Only fifth X, used for 19% against the European average of 21%. &nbsp;<br> &nbsp;
<h2> Attention to Fake news</h2>
According to the European Parliament's survey, a significant majority (76%) of young people - at European level - believes to have been previously exposed to misinformation and fake news.
In nine EU countries, more than half of the respondents reported that they were exposed to "often" or "very often" disinformation in the last 7 days, with the highest percentages in Malta (59%)>, Hungary >(58%), Greece (57%), Luxembourg >(55%) and Belgium (54%). The perception of Italians is 40%.> On the other hand, the percentage of those who believe they have never been exposed to misinformation and fake news> is the highest in Romania (19%), followed by Bulgaria (11%).
<br Among the major concerns for respondents, finally, there is an increase in prices and the cost of living, indicated by 40% of participants in the survey against 34% in Italy. A third of the sample (33%) stated that the EU should focus on the environment and climate change over the next five years (46% in Italy), while 31% (38% in Italy) believes that the economic situation and job creation should be a priority. Almost three out of ten (29%), moreover, want the EU to give priority to social protection, welfare and access to health care, since it stands at 34% in Italy. More than one out of five interviewed finally indicated education and training (27%) as a priority, against 26% in Italy.&nbsp;

